Z80-Forth 
=========
This is a complete Z80 Forth-2 System for CP/M (1983–1984)Name: F2 (Forth-2)
Authors: Primarily Klaus-Dieter Krause, Institut für Angewandte Physik, Universität Bonn
Target: Z80 + CP/M
Date of last change: 15.10.1984


Purpose and Historical Context
==============================
This is a full Forth development environment tailored for laboratory use. In the 1980s, Forth was extremely popular in physics
and instrumentation labs because it is compact, interactive, extremely fast on small machines, and allows direct hardware access.

Main Features of this System
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Feature                Description
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Forth Kernel           Standard threaded interpretive language with NEXT in Z80 assembly
CP/M Integration       Full BDOS file handling, console I/O, printer support
Block/Screen System    Classic Forth screen-based source (.SL2 files)
Memory Layout          Carefully tuned for Z80 (user area, stacks, buffers)
Terminal Control       ESC sequences for cursor positioning and screen clear
Extensibility          CREATE / DOES> , vocabularies, assembler support
I/O Redirection        KEY$ , EMIT$ , LOAD$ vectors for easy customization
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Code Structure Overview
=======================
ORIG:   Cold start and warm start vectors
NEXT:   The inner interpreter (very optimized Z80 code)
Colon / Semicolon / LIT / BRANCH etc.:   Core control structures
Low-level primitives: U*, U/, CMOVE, port I/O (P@ P!)
CP/M layer:         File operations (OPEN, READS, @FILE), DANA (get filename)
High-level Forth:   Interpreter, compiler, error handling, numeric conversion
User variables:     From S0 to WARM$ in the user area

The system uses indirect threaded code (common for Z80 Forth).



